Hi Mr Lee, I believe public morale is quite low in Singapore as it seems like our measures are out of control, or the government is on the course of getting everyone in Singapore infected with covid 19, while ministers have realistically low probabilities of being infected themselves as they don't take public transport and don't live in the densely populated public housing. I am actually disappointed that ordinary Singaporean lives and health (at risk due to possible long covid side effects) are being sacrificed because our ministers don't have a better plan of improving the economy while keeping Singaporeans safe. In addition, a large proportion of vaccinated Singaporeans have underlying health conditions and would be at risk of death if they contract covid. I believe every country is unique in their approach to managing covid due to difference in values and population size. Although living with covid seems to work well in places like London and new york cities, we do see examples like Israel where the population has high dependency on booster shots. I hope our ministers would think more deeply on a unique strategy that would be more appropriate for Singapore where we are still relatively a young nation and the lives of seniors lost are those of a generation who built up our nation. Their lives matter regardless of their choice to get vaccinated or if they have other health conditions. As Singapore has quite a sizeable proportion of seniors with underlying health conditions like diabetes and kidney failure, our death rates for vaccinated individuals could be high. Do we really want to be a nation where we are willing to sacrifice the lives of less healthy Singaporeans due to ministers who are unable to come up with better policies?
